What are the elemental, loop and node equations for this circuit?

Nodes \begin{equation} i = i \end{equation} \begin{equation} T_m = T_b+T_J+T_r \end{equation} \begin{equation} F_r=F_m \end{equation}

Loops \begin{equation} V_{1g} = V_{12}+V_{2g} \end{equation}

Elements \begin{equation} V_{12}=iR \end{equation} \begin{equation} k_t i = T_m \end{equation} \begin{equation} k_t \Omega_{1g} = V_{2g} \end{equation} \begin{equation} T_b = b\Omega_{1g} \end{equation} \begin{equation} T_J = J\dot{\Omega}_{1g} \end{equation} \begin{equation} T_r = rF_r \end{equation} \begin{equation} v_{1g} = r\Omega_{1g} \end{equation} \begin{equation} F_m = m\dot{v}_{1g} \end{equation}

How can we characterize a first-order response numerically?

How can we characterize a first-order response's transient behavior?

How can we characterize a first-order response's transient behavior?

Given a linear differential equation of the form $a_1\dot{y} + a_0y = b_0U$, we can use the time constant to characterize its transient behavior.

Time Constant

  • For a first order system, the system's single eigenvalue is $p=-\frac{a_0}{a_1}$.
  • We define the time constant to be $\tau = \frac{a_1}{a_0} = -\frac{1}{p}$ WHY? When $t = \tau$, then the differential equation's homogeneous solution is \begin{equation} y_h(t) = y_0e^{-\frac{t}{\tau}} = y_oe^{-1} = 0.367879y_0 \end{equation}

This means that if $y(\tau) = 0.368 y_0$, then approximately 63.2% of the change from $t_0$ to $t_{ss}$ has occurred when $t=\tau$. For step responses, this means that the time constant can be pulled off of a plot by finding the time $\tau$ at which $y(t) = 0.632(y_{ss}-y_0)$.

How can we characterize a first-order response's steady state behavior?

How can we characterize a first-order response's steady state behavior?

Steady State Gain $\equiv \frac{\Delta y_{ss}}{\Delta U_{ss}}$

Given a first-order linear differential equation of the form $a_1\dot{y} + a_0y = b_0U$, setting $\dot{y}=0$ to indicate steady state, and solving for the change in our output at steady state yields

$$\Delta y_{ss} = y_{ss}-y_0 = \left(U_{ss} - U_0\right)\frac{b_0}{a_0}$$

This allows us to write an equation for "steady state gain" using the first-order differential equation's $a_0$ and $b_0$ terms.

$$K_{ss} = \frac{y_{ss}-y_0}{U-U_0} = \frac{\Delta y_{ss}}{\Delta u_{ss}} = \frac{b_0}{a_0} $$

Solving for $\tau$ and $K_{ss}$ for your Romi data will allow you to compare these numbers with your model to solve for unknown parameters!

This will be your challenge for Assignment 6 (upcoming).

Calibrating and characterizing sensors

so far in ES302, you've used three types of sensors to varying degrees

  • Rotary Encoders that measure Romi's drive wheel motion
  • infrared distance sensors on the Romi's arm
  • Rotary potentiometers

Rotary encoders provide angular position measurements in "counts"

The Romi's wheel motors are each equipped with a rotary encoder. The conversion from counts to radians depends on the gear ratio, counts per revolution, etc. and can be computed using dimensional analysis. Assuming a 1:1 gear ratio, an example is provided below.

\begin{equation} \require{cancel} rad = \frac{\cancel{rev}}{\cancel{count}}\times\frac{2\pi \:rad}{\cancel{rev}} \end{equation}

How do wheel radians relate to Romi forward motion?

If we assume no-slip between the Romi tires and ground, we can model this relationship using the arc-length formula! \begin{equation} \frac{d}{dt}x = r \frac{d}{dt}\theta \end{equation} \begin{equation} v = r \omega \end{equation}

Rotary potentiometers measure the position of each of Romi's servos.

A rotary potentiometer is simply an adjustable voltage divider!

\begin{equation}V_{out} = V_{in}\frac{R_1}{R_1+R_2}\end{equation}

Rotary potentiometers measure the position of each of Romi's servos.

An analog to digital converted converts voltages between 0 and 5V on an Arduino "analog pin" to a 10-bit number, meaning that the relationship between ADC "counts" and "volts" can be derived analytically:

Text(0.5, 0, 'Counts')

\begin{equation} \require{cancel} V = \cancel{counts} \times \frac{5.0V}{1023\cancel{counts}} \end{equation}

However, this doesn't give the conversion between volts at the potentiometer wiper and servo arm degrees!

Sometimes conversions are easier with experimental data

Converting counts to volts on the servos' rotary potentiometers doesn't help convert to position! If I move the servo (by hand, for example) to two known positions, I can produce a best-fit line using point-slope form. Let's say I let a servo achieve steady-state at 90 degrees, and 110 degrees, and then read the potentiometer value in counts.

After finding the slope between your two known points, can then find the degree value for any count value using that slope and one of your known combinations of degrees and counts: \begin{equation} deg = m(counts-counts_{known})+deg_{known} \end{equation}

This is not as accurate as a true "linear fit" because it does not account for noise! If you wanted to use a true linear fit, you could consult this section from ES103.

IR distance sensors are highly nonlinear!

the reading given by the sensor is often very sensitive to IR reflectivity of the environment.

Sometimes, producing a lookup table and using linear interpolation (either using numpy.interp or manually with point-slope form) is the best way to convert from IR "counts" to meters.
